<font color="#FF0000">SEPARATION</font><br>
<tt>Sat Apr 19 20:08:10 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Well, Barry, you said if you were wrong you would get your head handed to you.  I guess it has been.<br>
The Vietnamese were very easy targets for my anger.  When I lived in Huntington Beach a bunch of us used to regularly &quot;search and destroy&quot; those signs along the 405.  As I worked through this thing I learned that these folks here have made a life for themselves as best as they know how.  The area of Little Siagon in Garden Grove was across the street from Westminster Harley so I got to see a lot of the building.  Little Siagon was built in run down area of Garden Grove and since has brought millions in tax revenue to the city of Garden Grove.  I worked with two Vietnamese and discovered much to my &quot;dismay&quot; (?) that they were a hard working, polite, and extremely intelligent.  So where now could I place my anger?  The obvious was gone because these folks had become personalized.  They were no longer &quot;gooks&quot; but were Vihn and Trang.  Difficult as well when one of them pointed out that he was only three when I was incountry! That was a slap of reality up side my head!  <br>
All anybody asked for is a little respect and kindness.  Is it not deserving of a group of people who survived the horror to get here?  I, personally, have never met a Vietnamese that with a little respect and understanding was not a fine person.  I guess I have been lucky.  Because I sure have met quite a few &quot;Americans&quot; that I wouldn't throw water on if they were on fire.<br>
  So, Lien,  Most Vets respect and admire the Vietnamese people.  It is just tough at time to seperate the Vietnamese people from the Vietnam War.
